        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>No counsel, industrie, or ualour sufficient against a Captaine so cunning, craftie, hardie, laborious, &amp; 
                        valiant at aduantage, as Annibal alwaies prooued himself. Till at the last Fortune tooke Scipios part, and made his uertu admirably uictorious.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Hannibal"/>
                    <person name="Fortuna"/>
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Annibal, qualis et quantus: etiam hostiu[m] confessione.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Hannibal"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>How remarkable and great Hanniabal was, even by admission of his enemies.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Scipio hostibus qu&agrave;[m] formidabilis.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>How formidable Scipio was to his enemies.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="hostis fiducia">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Magnifica Scipionis fidutia: divinum prognosticon Victoria[e].
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Scipioâ€™s splendid confidence: a divine prophesy of victory.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Annibal, pri&ugrave;s Animo victus; quid mirum, si statim Corpore vinceretur? Qualis Animi, Corporisq[ue] vis, talis Fortuna. 
                        Bello forsan vincere potuisset Annibal, callidior, atq[ue] patientior: pra[e]lio vicit animosior: nec tam ide&ograve; confidentior, 
                        quia validior, quam ide&ograve; validior, quia confidentior. Quod satis est virium, sufficit: ca[e]tera rerum momenta Arte militari, 
                        et Fidutia geruntur.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Hannibal"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Hannibal was first defeated mentally; small wonder that he would be defeated physically at once. 
                Fortune is as good as one's strength of mind and body. A more cunning and unyielding Hannibal could perhaps have won in warfare. 
                In the fight the bolder won, and one is not more confident to the same extent because one is stronger, as one is stronger, 
                because one is more confident. Enough strength suffices: the remaining stages of affairs are dealt with through military skill and 
                confidence.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
